  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Letter of Wine and Fruit Sent to the Mongol General's Command, for the Central Government
  author: Lee Gyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the [blank] day of the [blank] month, I humbly submit this letter to the honored official's command.

    As early spring arrives, I bow in reverence and inquire after your esteemed person. From afar, I gaze upon you with longing hope.

    Our nation has long suffered under the raids of the Khitans, a sickness lodged deep within our body that we could not expel alone. How could we have dared hope that you, great General, would undertake this righteous campaign for our humble realm, sweeping away the shame and filth, traveling far through wind and frost to expose yourself to hardship? Truly, it was our duty to offer you the courtesy of provisions to ease your soldiers' toil. Yet at first we knew not the day your great army would cross our borders, and we were hampered by the bandits' blockade of the roads. This delay in paying our respects weighs upon me with shame and trepidation. I beg your magnanimous forgiveness.

    When we first heard that the rebels had retreated into Jiangdong City to defend themselves, we thought them already trapped as caged beasts—no cause for concern. We prepared to send word expressing our gratitude and inquiring after your welfare. But before our messenger could depart, urgent news arrived: the rebels had indeed abandoned the city, surrendered of their own accord, and were all beheaded or taken captive. The entire nation rejoiced, and we clapped our hands together in shared celebration. This is the true virtue of a great nation extending its strength to aid the weak and succor its neighbors—for us, a fortunate encounter that comes once in ten thousand generations. Overwhelmed by such kindness, we know not how to repay it.

    Humbly receiving the royal command, we have prepared modest offerings of wine, fruit, and ceremonial gifts. We have entrusted these to officials [names omitted] to present to you, with a detailed inventory provided in a separate dispatch. We humbly beseech you not to refuse these humble tokens on account of their meagerness, nor to fault us for the delay in their delivery. I remain anxious and ashamed.
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal diplomatic letter sent on behalf of the Korean state (Goryeo) to a Mongol military commander who has aided them against Khitan raiders. The letter employs the conventions of official correspondence between subordinate and superior states.
    - 'Jiangdong City (江東城): A historical reference to a fortified position where rebels had taken refuge before surrendering to Mongol forces.'
    - The repeated phrase 'I bow in reverence' and 'anxious and ashamed' (황공) reflects the formal protocol of diplomatic submission and gratitude required in medieval East Asian statecraft.
